Today I'd like to honor my colleague Rep. Sam Johnson's "Returniversary" after being held captive as a POW for nearly seven years. This photo was taken on this day in 1973, when he landed in Texas and saw his family for the first time. Rep. Johnson was awarded two Silver Stars, two Legions of Merit, the Distinguished Flying Cross, one Bronze Star with Valor, two Purple Hearts, four Air Medals, and three Outstanding Unit Awards for his devoted service in the United States Air Force.

Legendary Texas Ranger and frontiersman "Big Foot" Wallace was born #OnThisDay 200 years ago. Born in Kentucky, Wallace quickly headed to the Republic of Texas after learning of his brother's death in combat during the Texas Revolution. He made Texas his home, devoting his career as a Texas Ranger to tirelessly defending the state against enemy attacks. In exchange for his service, the state of Texas granted him land in what is now #TX23, along the Medina River and in Frio County.

#OnThisDay in 1871, the Texas legislature approved a bill to organize what is now the great Texas A&M University. Opening in October 1876 with just 106 students, the oldest public institution of higher education in Texas now has more than 64,000 students and 436,000 former students nationwide. Gig'em!

Texas forces led by General Sam Houston launched a surprise attack against General Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna's Mexican army at the San Jacinto #OnThisDay in 1836. The Battle of San Jacinto was the final battle of the Texas Revolution and lasted only 18 minutes. After being taken prisoner, Santa Anna signed a treaty recognizing Texas' independence in exchange for his freedom.

#OnThisDay in 1898, Gen. Nelson A. Miles ordered the First United States Volunteer Cavalry Regiment, better known as the "Rough Riders," from San Antonio, Texas to Tampa, Florida, to take part in the forthcoming invasion of Cuba as part of the Spanish-American War.   The fame of the Rough Riders catapulted Roosevelt into the vice presidency and later the presidency of the United States. In San Antonio, in addition to Roosevelt Park, Roosevelt St and the Roosevelt Bar of the Menger Hotel, a favorite watering place of the regiment, are named in memory of their sojourn in Texas.

For #ImmigrantHeritageMonth here's another #tbt of Scheduler Nancy Pack's great-grandfather Benjamin Pack, whose parents Harris Pachmelitzki and Ethel Pachwell arrived in NYC from Russia, married and changed their name to Pack. Nancyâ€™s great grandmother, Ida Winograd Pack (Winnie, pictured below), immigrated from Belarus via London aboard the Steam Ship St. Louis in 1902. Benjamin and Winnie had three children Howard, Jay and Ethel, the oldest being Nancy's grandfather Howard Pack. Ben was in business in NYC as a Factor, who is someone that lends borrowed money to a business and in his case Furriers. Most of the Furriers in NYC immigrated from Russia and a few from Greece. Benâ€™s son Howard also worked in the fur trade, but decided to start a side venture and joined with a group of Greek Furriers who decided to leave the fur business with an opportunity to buy a single surplus ship from the US Government, after the end of World War II.
